## Phase 0 – Advanced Mindset + Setup (First 30–90 Days)

### 1. Mindset for Ahead Students
- You are early — use it to build something big
- Quality > quantity: one excellent hard problem > 10 normal ones
- Balance college + code + rest + friends — no burnout
- Make real impact: real users, Kaggle submissions, open-source PRs, internships
- Post smart & consistent on LinkedIn — recruiters will find you

### 2. Simple & Powerful Tracking
Use one Google Sheet or Notion page only.  
Write these columns every week:

Week | DSA (Medium/Hard) | ML/DL Project Work | Internship Applied | Kaggle/HF Submission | One Big Win | Energy (1–10)

Sunday 30–60 min review:
- Re-solve 6–10 hard/medium problems you struggled with
- Update project progress or metrics
- Send 5–10 LinkedIn messages to seniors/alumni
- Plan next week (example: “focus on CNN + Kaggle competition”)

### 3. Make Your Online Presence Strong
LinkedIn  
- Headline: B.Tech CSE AIML '29 | 800+ DSA | ML & Deep Learning | Looking for AI Internships 2027–2028  
- About: 6–8 lines — write about DSA count, ML/DL projects, Kaggle, open-source, why you love AI  
- Post 2–3 times/week: simple explanation of model, project demo, Kaggle rank update  

GitHub  
- Bio: First-Year CSE AIML • ML/DL • 800+ DSA • Building AI Projects  
- Pin 8–10 best repos  
- Every repo: add diagram, results, notebooks, live deploy link  

Kaggle / Hugging Face  
- Make profile active  
- Submit 5–10 notebooks  
- Try competitions — aim bronze/silver medals  

### 4. Daily Routine (College + Advanced Balance)
Normal College Days (2.5–4 hours)  
- 1–1.5 hours DSA (2–4 medium/hard problems)  
- 1 hour ML/DL project or model training  
- 30–45 min theory / video / paper reading  
- 20 min application or LinkedIn post  

Free Days / Weekends (5–7 hours)  
- 2 hours DSA + mock contest  
- 2 hours project or model training  
- 1 hour DL theory / paper / video  
- 45 min outreach / applications  

### 5. Health & No Burnout Rules
- Sleep 7+ hours every night  
- Walk, play or exercise 30–45 min daily  
- One easy day per week (revision + relax)  
- Talk to friends/family — don’t code all day  
- Eat normal food — brain needs energy  

## Phase 1 – Advanced DSA + ML/DL Depth (Months 1–12 of Second Year)

### 1. DSA – Strong Medium + Hard Level
Focus: Master medium + learn hard patterns (company style)

Monthly Plan  
Months 1–3  
- Advanced arrays/strings: Kadane variants, sliding window hard, two pointers deep  
- Binary search hard: rotated array variants, kth smallest advanced  
- Linked list/Stack/Queue hard: LRU cache full, next greater both sides  

Months 4–6  
- Recursion/Backtracking: subsets II, permutations II, N-Queens, word break II  
- Trees/BST: diameter, LCA, kth smallest BST  
- Graphs medium: BFS/DFS grid, shortest path intro  

Months 7–9  
- Heaps hard: median in stream, task scheduler  
- Greedy/DP 1D: knapsack variants, LIS, house robber  
- Company medium-hard problems (Amazon, Microsoft, Google tagged)  

Months 10–12  
- Mock contests (LeetCode weekly/biweekly, Codeforces virtual)  
- Revision cycles (solve again after 7/30/90 days)  

Target: 900–1400 total problems (600–900 medium, 200–400 hard)  

Resources  
- Striver SDE Sheet + A2Z DSA  
- Love Babbar company-specific lists  
- takeUforward hard series  
- LeetCode company tags  

### 2. Machine Learning – Intermediate to Advanced
Topics  
- Feature engineering deep (scaling, encoding, missing values)  
- Ensemble methods (XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost, stacking)  
- Imbalanced data handling (SMOTE, class weight, undersampling)  
- Hyperparameter tuning (GridSearch, RandomSearch, Optuna)  
- Pipelines & MLflow for tracking experiments  

Projects  
1. Customer segmentation (advanced clustering)  
2. Fraud detection (imbalanced classification with XGBoost)  
3. Sales forecasting (time series basics)  
4. Credit risk model (ensemble + tuning)  
5. Kaggle competition (aim top 20–30% rank)  

### 3. Deep Learning – Intermediate Level
Topics  
- CNN advanced: transfer learning (EfficientNet, ResNet, MobileNet)  
- RNN/LSTM basics (time series prediction, text generation)  
- Transformers intro (BERT, Hugging Face basics)  
- GANs simple (DCGAN for image generation)  
- Vision & NLP projects  

Projects  
1. Custom CNN for image classification  
2. Sentiment analysis with fine-tuned BERT  
3. Text summarizer using T5/BART  
4. Face recognition system  
5. Object detection basics (YOLOv5/YOLOv8 intro)  

Tools  
- PyTorch or TensorFlow/Keras (choose one)  
- Google Colab (free GPU)  
- Hugging Face Transformers library  

